Surrounding Context¶

The work that youve done to date has garnered enough favor that youve been allocated additional funding to continue your research. However, in order to secure the additional funding, your manager had to agree to have you present your analysis and findings at the upcoming meeting with the companys Senior Vice Presidents. Representatives from Audit and Legal will also be in attendance. Given the visibility of this upcoming presentation, your manager has requested an outline of your presentation in advance of the meeting. Also, given the increased emphasis on data security and privacy, your manager wants to be briefed on the ethical and security considerations ahead of time. Your manager recognizes time may prohibit detailed discussion of these items during the presentation, but he/she would like to include your briefing in the appendix.

In general, your manager has given you very little direction regarding the desired structure of the presentation. However, he/she did outline some required content below. The current expectation is that you will be allotted a ten-minute time slot in the upcoming meeting.

Update¶

Your manager confirmed you will be allotted ten minutes at the upcoming senior management meeting. He/she also indicated there is quite a bit of interest in your topic, and that a few senior data scientists have been invited to sit in. Your manager emphasized how important this opportunity was and encouraged you to over-prepare. The agenda is run pretty tight and running long (or even too short) is judged very critically.

Normally documentation is due in advance of the meeting; however, your manager negotiated an extension by providing the outline he shared with you earlier (included below).

Presentation Outline

  • General Business Context
  • Specific Question Being Answered
  • Analysis Methods
  • Summary of Findings & Next Steps

He/she also committed you to providing copies of the following deliverables:

  1. Presentation delivered in the meeting (PowerPoint, PDF, etc.)
  2. Presentation appendix - Data Privacy/Ethics Memo (Word)
  3. Final version of code (HTML)

# replace contractions
# code borrowed from http://stackoverflow.com/questions/27845796/replacing-words-matching-regular-expressions-in-python
import re

replacement_patterns = [
(r'won\'t', 'will not'),
(r'can\'t', 'cannot'),
(r'i\'m', 'i am'),
(r'i\'ve', 'i have'),
(r'ain\'t', 'is not'),
(r'isn\'t', 'is not'),
(r'it\'s', 'it is'),
(r'(\w+)\'ll', '\g<1> will'),
(r'(\w+)n\'t', '\g<1> not'),
(r'(\w+)\'ve', '\g<1> have'),
(r'(\w+)\'s', '\g<1> is'),
(r'(\w+)\'re', '\g<1> are'),
(r'(\w+)\'d', '\g<1> would'),
(r'we\'ve', 'we have'),
(r'what\'s', 'what is')
]

class RegexpReplacer(object):
    def __init__(self, patterns=replacement_patterns):
        self.patterns = [(re.compile(regex), repl) for (regex, repl) in patterns]
    def replace(self, text):
        s = text
        for (pattern, repl) in self.patterns:
            (s, count) = re.subn(pattern, repl, s)
        return s

The function below removes hashtag, @user, and hyperlinks from tweet text.

In [14]:
# code borrowed from https://stackoverflow.com/questions/8376691/how-to-remove-hashtag-user-link-of-a-tweet-using-regular-expression

import string

def strip_links(text):
    link_regex    = re.compile('((https?):((//)|(\\\\))+([\w\d:#@%/;$()~_?\+-=\\\.&](#!)?)*)', re.DOTALL)
    links         = re.findall(link_regex, text)
    for link in links:
        text = text.replace(link[0], ', ')    
    return text

def strip_all_entities(text):
    entity_prefixes = ['@','#']
    for separator in  string.punctuation:
        if separator not in entity_prefixes :
            text = text.replace(separator,' ')
    words = []
    for word in text.split():
        word = word.strip()
        if word:
            if word[0] not in entity_prefixes:
                words.append(word)
    return ' '.join(words)

# here we are going for strictly the sum:  add up the positives and "subtract" the negatives
# you can return a number or a label

def afinn_sent(inputstring):
    
    sentcount =0
    for word in inputstring.split():  
        if word.rstrip('?:!.,;') in afinn:
            sentcount = sentcount + afinn[word.rstrip('?:!.,;')]
            
    
    if (sentcount < 0):
        sentiment = 'Negative'
    elif (sentcount >0):
        sentiment = 'Positive'
    else:
        sentiment = 'Neutral'
    
    return sentiment

# different dictionary
# different measure

def hl_sent(inputstring):

    poscount = 0
    negcount = 0
    
    for word in inputstring.split(): 
        if HLpos.count(word.rstrip('?:!.,;')):
            poscount +=1
        elif HLneg.count(word.rstrip('?:!.,;')):
            negcount +=1
     
    
    if poscount+negcount > 0:
        t = float((poscount - negcount)/(poscount+negcount))    
    else:
        t = 0
    
    
    if t > 0:
        tone = "Positive"
    elif t < 0:
        tone = "Negative"
    else:
        tone = "Neutral"
    
    return tone

def afinn_sent2(inputstring):
    
    sentcount =0
    i=0
    

    for word in inputstring.split():
        prev = inputstring.split().pop(i-1)

        if word in afinn:
            if (prev == 'no'):
                sentcount = sentcount - afinn[word] - afinn[prev]
            elif (prev == 'not'):
                sentcount = sentcount - afinn[word]
            else:
                sentcount = sentcount + afinn[word]
            i+=1
    
    if (sentcount < 0):
        sentiment = 'Negative'
    elif (sentcount >0):
        sentiment = 'Positive'
    else:
        sentiment = 'Neutral'
    
    
    return sentiment
